#: ../../source/general.rst:0
#: ../../source/general.rst:0
msgid "Note2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:892
msgid "For the Heatblur F-14 in DCS the external ECS air supply is connected via the same command as the engine starter air."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:896
msgid "Oxygen System"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:898
msgid "The F-14 carries one or two 10-liter liquid oxygen bottles providing oxygen to the crew when needed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:900
msgid "The oxygen supply is controlled on the pilot :ref:`oxygen` and RIO :ref:`roxyvent` respectively. Both panels contain an **OXYGEN** switch that sets oxygen supply to **ON** or **OFF**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:903
msgid "Liquid oxygen remaining is shown on the :ref:`liqoxyqtyind` on the pilot's right side console. The gauge shows remaining liters of liquid oxygen up to 20 liters (if two bottles are installed). The indicator is electrically driven and if it receives no power an **OFF** flag will be visible and it will display 0 liters remaining."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:907
msgid "Additionally the RIO :ref:`cauadvpanel` has the **OXY LOW** caution light which illuminates when the liquid oxygen quantity is below 2 liters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:909
msgid "During the **INST** test on the ref:`MTPanel` the liquid oxygen meter shows 2 liters and the **OXY LOW** caution light illuminates."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:913
msgid "Flight Instruments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:915
msgid "Apart from the VDIG (HUD and VDI) the F-14 is equipped with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:917
msgid "two :ref:`stbyattind` (and :ref:`rstbyattind`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:918
msgid "two :ref:`pspeedmachind` (and :ref:`rspeedmachind`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:919
msgid "two :ref:`pservopneualt` (and :ref:`rservopneualt`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:920
msgid "a :ref:`vertvelind`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:921
msgid "a turn and slip indicator (on the :ref:`ACMpanel`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:922
msgid "an :ref:`acc`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:923
msgid "a :ref:`pstbycomp`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:924
msgid "and two mechanical clocks (:ref:`pclock` and :ref:`rclock`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:926
msgid "The types that have two installed have one installed on the RIO instrument panel as well as the pilot one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:928
msgid "All of these instruments that need electrical power are connected to the essential buses meaning that they can be powered by the emergency generator if the main ones fail."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:930
msgid "For more info on the instruments see their respective cockpit panel descriptions linked above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:934
msgid "Canopy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:936
msgid "The rear-hinged F-14 canopy is operated hydraulically and pneumatically. Controls are present in both pilot and RIO cockpits."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:939
msgid "See :ref:`pcanopylever` or :ref:`rcanopylever` for the controls."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:941
msgid "The **CANOPY** caution light on both the pilot :ref:`CAindicator` and the rio :ref:`cauadvpanel` illuminates if the canopy is not in the down and locked, secured position."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:945
msgid "Ejection System"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:947
msgid "The F-14 Tomcat is equipped with dual Martin-Baker GRU-7A rocket-assisted ejection seats, one for the pilot, one for the RIO. The ejection system is a zero/zero system, capable of successfully ejecting the crewmembers at zero airspeed, stationary, on the ground."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:950
msgid "As the F-14 is a two seat aircraft it has additional controls apart from the ejection handles and arming systems, namely the ejection command lever. This lever, which is located in the RIO cockpit, selects if the RIO ejects the pilot as well when he ejects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:953
msgid "The lever is situated beside the sensor control panel, see :ref:`ejectcmdlev`. When set to **PILOT**, the pilot ejects both crewmembers, while the RIO ejects only himself. When set to **MCO** both crewmembers eject both crewmembers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:957
msgid "The system does not allow pilot-only ejection because it would be undesirable for the RIO to remain in the aircraft alone."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:959
msgid "The pilot has indication of what position the ejection command lever is at on the :ref:`gearcontrol`, the **EJECT CMD** flip-flop indicator showing **PILOT** when the lever is in pilot and **MCO** when in MCO."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:961
msgid "If the canopy does not jettison when initiating the ejection sequence it's possible to manually jettison it using the :ref:`pcanjett` in the pilot cockpit or the :ref:`rcanjett` in the RIO cockpit. If the canopy inhibited ejection after ejection initiation, jettisoning the canopy will most likely restart it. If ejection is needed during a flat spin, it's also recommended to manually jettison the canopy and allow it to clear before initiating the ejection sequence as the canopy might need longer to clear during a flat spin."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:967
msgid "Lighting System"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:969
msgid "The F-14 Tomcat lighting system consists of the internal and the external lights."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:971
msgid "The internal lights are the red instrument panel and console lights, red and white floodlights and a moveable utility light at both crew stations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:973
msgid "The external lights are the position lights, the anticollision lights, the formation lights, the taxi light, the approach lights and the refueling probe light."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:977
msgid "Internal Lighting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:979
msgid "The red instrument panel and console lights are the normally used lights during nighttime, they back-light all instruments and controls allowing their use while impacting night vision minimally."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:981
msgid "The floodlights allow for additional lighting of the cockpit panels but care should be taken to avoid affecting night vision."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:983
msgid "The utility lights are movable and can be used to illuminate a specific spot and as a map or reading light."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:985
msgid "Controls for the internal lights are on the :ref:`mlightctrlpanel` in pilot cockpit and :ref:`intlight` in the RIO cockpit, each controlling their own cockpit lighting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:987
msgid "The utility light function is not modelled in DCS but the flashlight function, default keybind Left Alt + L, which moves with the cursor can be used, providing a similar function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:991
msgid "External Lighting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:993
msgid "The position lights on the F-14 are located on the left wing tip (red), right wing tip (green), top aft of left vertical stabilizer (white) and upper and lower lights on the wing gloves on each side (red on left glove and green on right). The glove lights are additional lights supplementing the wing tip lights. When the wings are swept forward of 25° the wing tip lights are active and when aft of 25° the glove lights are active instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:996
msgid "With the gear down, wings forward of 25° and the position lights in steady mode both the glove and wingtip position lights are lit. When the anticollision lights are on the the position lights can only operate in the steady mode, otherwise they can be set to flash."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:999
msgid "The anticollision lights are located on the chin pod or TCS pod, top front of the left vertical stabilizer and top aft of the right vertical stabilizer. The anticollision lights are all red flashing lights. The chin pod mounted lower light only operates while the nosegear wheel door is closed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1002
msgid "The formation lights are dim green lights used for formation flight which can be dimmed gradually. They are located on the aircraft nose (behind the radome), the wing tips, on the fuselage aft of the wings and on the top edge of the vertical stabilizers. All are duplicated on both sides of the aircraft."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1005
msgid "The taxi light is a fixed headlight located on the nosewheel strut. It's automatically turned off with gear retraction if set to on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1007
msgid "The approach lights are also located on the nosewheel strut and replicate the AoA indexer for the LSOs during carrier traps."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1009
msgid "The refueling probe light is used to illuminate the refueling probe and is automatically enabled with probe extension."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1011
msgid "All external light controls are located on the :ref:`mlightctrlpanel` except for the exterior lights switch on the left throttle (see :ref:`throttle`) which disables or enables all external lights apart from the approach lights."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1015
msgid "Jettison System"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1017
msgid "The Jettison system has four modes of operation: emergency, ACM, selective and auxiliary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1020
msgid "**Emergency Jettison**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1022
msgid "The emergency jettison is selected via the **EMERG STORES JETT** on the :ref:`gearcontrol`. Selection causes the **EMERG JETT** caution light to illuminate on the pilot :ref:`CAindicator`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1025
msgid "The emergency jettison requires only no weight on wheels indicated (no master arm) and ejects all stores except for Sidewinders."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1028
msgid "**ACM Jettison**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1030
msgid "The ACM jettison is selected via the **ACM JETT** button under the ACM cover/switch on the :ref:`ACMpanel`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1032
msgid "The ACM jettison, like the emergency jettison, requires no master arm but instead requires that the landing gear lever is up. Unlike the emergency jettison the ACM jettison only ejects those stations selected by the RIO on the :ref:`armpanel` (set to **SEL** or **B** for stations 1 and 8)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1036
msgid "**Selective Jettison**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1038
msgid "The selective jettison is set and executed by the RIO on the :ref:`armpanel`. This mode of jettisoning requires the landing gear handle to be in the up position and the master arm to be on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1041
msgid "The procedure for jettison in selective mode is to set the desired station switches to **SEL** and hold the **SEL JETT** switch to **JETT**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1044
msgid "**Auxiliary Jettison**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1046
msgid "The auxiliary jettison mode is a backup mode to use when the other modes have failed. Like the selective jettison mode it requires the landing gear handle to be up and the master arm to be on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1049
msgid "This mode can only eject air-to-ground stores and ejects them by actuating the normal release hooks. This means that the aircraft needs to fly straight and level as the stores are not ejected forcefully but instead just released and cleared using gravity."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1052
msgid "No jettison mode can jettison ITERs or stores loaded on those, they need to be dropped like normal, with or without the fuzes armed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1056
msgid "CADC Central Air Data Computer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1058
msgid "The Central Air Data Computer or CADC is the computer acting as the spider in the web for most aircraft flight sensors and relaying this information to all systems needing them. In addition it also controls the wing-sweep via the wing-sweep schedule and also controls the flaps and slats as they are limited by that same schedule."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1063
msgid "AN/AWG-9 Weapon Control System (WCS)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1065
msgid "The AN/AWG-9 weapons control system (WCS) is an integrated system containing the F-14's main sensors and computer providing detection, tracking and engagement of targets in the air-to-air and air-to-ground roles."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1069
msgid "Detail Data Display (DDD) and Panel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1072
msgid "The DDD is the main control panel and display for the radar part of the AN/AWG-9 system. It contains all the controls for the radar except the scan volume and stabilization controls which are on the sensor control panel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1075
msgid "**TGTS, MLC, AGC and PARAMP Switches**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1077
msgid "The upper left part of the DDD panel contains four switches (**1-4**) controling amplification, mainlobe clutter (MLC) suppression and target size parameters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1079
msgid "The **TGTS** (targets) switch selects expected target size which is used by the WCS to calculate missile launch zones and set parameters for target tracking in the radar. It also sets the range at which the missile ATC is sent, **SMALL** being 6NM, **NORM** 10NM and **LARGE** 13NM. The selected position of this switch might negatively affect target tracking and engagement if set incorrectly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1081
msgid "The **MLC** switch controls how the system supresses the MLC in the radar system while in pulse doppler mode. The OUT position disables the system while the IN position enables it. The AUTO position automatically enables the MLC filter if the antenna look-up angle is less than 3°."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1083
msgid "The **AGC** switch controls the automatic gain control and is used in the pulse doppler modes to allow control of the time constant used for the AGC. Normally (NORM position) the AGC uses a longer time constant to calculate a mean value used for amplification. If the radar is operating in a jammed environment or heavy clutter is present the AGC can be set to use a faster time constant to mitigate these factors but this setting can also make the radar less sensitive to real targets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1085
msgid "The **PARAMP**, parametric amplifier switch allows for manual control of the parametric amplifier which is used to amplify weaker targets in all radar modes. Normally the WCS controls when to use the PARAMP depending on range but if tracking an unusually strong target it can be used to disable PARAMP to lessen the effect from background noise. If set to off manually it lessens the detection range by approximately 35%."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1087
msgid "AGC, PARAMP and TGTS switches currently not implemented."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1090
msgid "**AWG-9 Range Selection and Tracking Indication**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1092
msgid "In the upper central part of the DDD panel are located the controls and indicators for setting the radar range in the search modes. Below these are also present the indicators for radar tracking while in the single target track (STT) modes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1095
msgid "The six round buttons (**8**), which are labelled **5, 10, 20, 50, 100 and 200**, are used to set desired radar range in pulse modes and IFF range, they also set the scale on the pilot target range displays. The buttons are mutually exclusive as only one range can be selected at a time. In pulse search this setting affects the PRF of the radar and the scale on the DDD and if set to 20nm or greater range it also enables pulse compression."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1099
msgid "The **range display drum** (**7**) indicates currently displayed scale on the DDD for the pulse modes and is blank when using pulse-doppler. It can also show ±10 for when using the IFF interrogator in the STT modes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1102
msgid "Below these are the four radar track indicator lights which are used to indicate how the radar tracks the target in STT."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1104
msgid "The **ANT TRK**, antenna track, light indicates that the radar is tracking the target angle (direction) in azimuth and elevation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1105
msgid "The **RDROT**, radar on target, light indicates that the target is in the range or rate gate and is being tracked in range or rate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/general.rst:1106
msgid "The **JAT**, jam angle track, indicates that the antenna is tracking a jamming source's angle in azimuth and elevation."
msgstr ""

